<speak version="1.0" xml:lang="en-US" xmlns:mstts="http://www.w3.org/2001/mstts">
  <voice name="en-US-JennyNeural">
    <prosody rate="0%" pitch="+0st">
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S1"/> Containerization is a method of packaging applications and their dependencies into a single unit.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S2"/> This makes deployment easier and more efficient.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S3"/> One of the key benefits of containerization is consistency across different environments.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S4"/> It helps eliminate the 'it works on my machine' problem.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S5"/> Containers are lightweight and share the host system's kernel.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S6"/> In contrast, virtual machines run a full operating system, making them heavier.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S7"/> Use cases for containerization include microservices architecture, continuous integration, and cloud-native applications.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S8"/> These scenarios benefit greatly from the flexibility containers provide.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S9"/> A common pitfall is assuming that containers are a one-size-fits-all solution.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S10"/> They work best for specific use cases, not every application.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S11"/> Let's check your understanding.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S12"/> Can you name a benefit of using containers over virtual machines?</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S13"/> Think about deployment speed and resource efficiency.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S14"/> To recap, containerization simplifies application deployment and management.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
      <p><bookmark mark="L1.S15"/> It offers consistency and efficiency, making it ideal for modern applications.</p>
<break time="300ms"/>
    </prosody>
  </voice></speak>